
1,"16q24.3 microdeletion syndrome","A rare genetic condition caused by a small deletion on chromosome 16 at position q24.3.",,6,6,"MONDO:0016838",1,"16q24.3 Microdeletion Syndrome","Developmental delay","Intellectual disability","Facial dysmorphism","Feeding difficulties","Hypotonia","Seizures","Cardiac anomalies","Skeletal abnormalities","16q24.3 microdeletion syndrome is characterized by variable clinical features, including developmental delay, intellectual disability, facial dysmorphism, and feeding difficulties. Additional features may include hypotonia, seizures, cardiac anomalies, and skeletal abnormalities.","Affected individuals typically exhibit developmental delays, particularly in speech and motor skills. Intellectual disability ranges from mild to severe. Facial features may include a prominent forehead, widely spaced eyes (hypertelorism), a broad nasal bridge, and a small chin (micrognathia). Feeding difficulties are common in infancy.","The syndrome is caused by a microdeletion on chromosome 16 at position q24.3. The size of the deletion can vary, and the specific genes affected contribute to the variability in clinical features. The deletion typically occurs de novo (new mutation) and is not inherited from parents.","Microdeletion on chromosome 16q24.3","De novo mutation","Variations in deletion size","Genes affected within the deleted region","NAN","Occupational therapy","Speech therapy","Nutritional support","Genetic counseling","Prenatal diagnosis","Newborn screening","NAN","Infancy to early childhood","De novo mutations in chromosome 16","Not typically inherited, usually a new mutation","Variable, depending on the size and location of deletion","Genetic testing (chromosomal microarray analysis)","Cardiac defects","Limited data available; prognosis depends on the severity of associated symptoms and complications.","Estimated to be rare, with fewer than 200 reported cases worldwide."
7,"16q24.3 microdeletion syndrome","Microdeletion of the 16q24.3 chromosomal region, characterized by intellectual disability and facial dysmorphism.","A rare chromosomal deletion syndrome involving the distal long arm of chromosome 16.",6,6,"MONDO:0016838",1,"16q24.3 microdeletion syndrome","Developmental delay","Intellectual disability","Facial dysmorphism","Feeding difficulties","Hypotonia","Growth retardation","Microcephaly","Seizures","Cardiac anomalies","16q24.3 microdeletion syndrome is a rare genetic disorder caused by the deletion of a small piece of chromosome 16 at position q24.3. This deletion results in the loss of several genes, leading to a variety of developmental and physical abnormalities. The severity of the syndrome can vary depending on the size and location of the deletion.","Common symptoms include developmental delay, intellectual disability, distinctive facial features, feeding difficulties, hypotonia, and growth retardation. Some individuals may also experience microcephaly, seizures, and cardiac anomalies.","The syndrome is caused by a spontaneous deletion of genetic material on chromosome 16 at position q24.3. This deletion is typically de novo, meaning it occurs randomly and is not inherited from the parents.","De novo deletion","Microdeletion on 16q24.3","Loss of multiple genes","NAN","NAN","Supportive care","Physical therapy","Occupational therapy","Genetic counseling","Prenatal testing (if deletion is identified in a parent)","NAN","NAN","Variable, often in infancy or early childhood","De novo mutation","No known inherited predisposition","Variable, ranging from mild to severe","Chromosomal microarray analysis (CMA)","Cardiac defects","NAN","Variable, dependent on the severity of the condition and access to appropriate medical care.","NAN"

7,"16q24.3 microdeletion syndrome","A rare genetic disorder characterized by a small deletion on chromosome 16, leading to developmental delays and dysmorphic features.","Deletion of a small portion of chromosome 16 at position 16q24.3.  This region contains multiple genes, and the loss of these genes results in a variety of symptoms.",6,6,"MONDO:0016838",1,"16q24.3 Microdeletion Syndrome","Developmental delay","Intellectual disability","Dysmorphic features","Feeding difficulties","Hypotonia","Microcephaly","Short stature","Cardiac anomalies","Seizures","Individuals with 16q24.3 microdeletion syndrome exhibit a range of symptoms, including developmental delays, intellectual disability, distinctive facial features (dysmorphic features), feeding difficulties, low muscle tone (hypotonia), small head size (microcephaly), short stature, heart defects (cardiac anomalies), and seizures. The severity of these symptoms can vary significantly from person to person.","The primary cause of 16q24.3 microdeletion syndrome is a deletion of genetic material on chromosome 16 at the 16q24.3 location. This deletion encompasses multiple genes, and the loss of these genes leads to the various symptoms associated with the syndrome.  The deletion usually occurs spontaneously (de novo) during the formation of reproductive cells (eggs or sperm) or in early embryonic development.","Microdeletion at 16q24.3","De novo mutation","Loss of multiple genes","NAN","NAN","NAN","Occupational therapy","Physical therapy","Speech therapy","NAN","Genetic counseling","NAN","Exposure to certain teratogens during pregnancy.","Varies; can be present at birth or identified in early childhood.","Deletion of genes in the 16q24.3 region.","Generally not inherited; usually a spontaneous (de novo) mutation.","Varies; can range from mild to severe depending on the size and location of the deletion.","Chromosomal microarray analysis (CMA)","Cardiac anomalies, feeding difficulties, developmental delay","Limited data available; estimated to be very rare.","Variable depending on the severity of the condition and specific complications."
